    "summary": "The Ottoman conquest of the Balkans (c. 1352–1453 AD) was one of the most significant geopolitical transformations of medieval Europe, as the expanding [[event:94|Ottoman Empire]] systematically absorbed the Balkan Peninsula — previously divided among Serbian, Bulgarian, Byzantine, and various other Christian kingdoms — establishing a Muslim Turkish presence in southeastern Europe that would endure for five centuries and shape the religious, ethnic, and political landscape of the region to the present day. The Ottomans crossed into Europe in 1352, seized Adrianople (Edirne) in 1369 making it their capital, and progressively absorbed Byzantine territory, Bulgarian kingdoms, Serbian principalities, and Bosnian lands through a combination of military conquest, dynastic marriage, and diplomatic subordination.\n\nThe conquest proceeded through several decisive engagements: the defeat of a Serbian-led coalition at the [[event:2317|Battle of Kosovo]] (1389); the destruction of a European crusading army at Nicopolis (1396); the defeat of another crusade at Varna (1444); and ultimately the [[event:2240|fall of Constantinople]] (1453) that completed the elimination of Byzantine political power. Ottoman administration of the Balkans introduced the millet system allowing Christian communities to maintain their religious and legal autonomy, the devshirme system drawing the Christian rural population's sons into Ottoman military-administrative service, and a land tenure system that reorganized existing agricultural arrangements. The Ottoman Balkan presence created the multi-religious, multi-ethnic complexity that defined the region through the 20th century, generating both moments of remarkable tolerance and devastating religious and ethnic conflicts that continued into the Yugoslav wars of the 1990s.",
